-- Update books with complete, longer content
UPDATE books 
SET content = 'In a magnificent castle perched atop a verdant hill, there lived a benevolent queen who cherished her subjects deeply. The castle''s elaborate gardens flourished with vibrant flowers and ancient oak trees that whispered tales of old.

Every morning, the queen would ascend to the highest tower to greet the sunrise. She believed that each new day brought fresh opportunities to spread kindness and wisdom throughout her realm. Her subjects adored her, not for her crown or riches, but for her compassionate heart and fair judgment.

One particularly memorable day, a young peasant girl arrived at the castle gates seeking an audience with the queen. The guards, initially hesitant to admit someone so plainly dressed, were persuaded by the girl''s earnest demeanor and allowed her entry.

The girl stood before the throne, trembling with both fear and excitement. "Your Majesty," she began, her voice barely above a whisper, "I come from the village beyond the eastern forest. Our crops have failed, and our people are struggling to survive the harsh winter ahead."

The queen listened intently, her expression growing increasingly concerned. "Tell me more, child," she said gently. "What assistance do you seek?"

"We need seeds for the spring planting and provisions to sustain us through the winter," the girl replied. "I promise that when our harvest comes, we shall repay your kindness tenfold."

The queen pondered this request thoughtfully. She knew that helping one village might inspire others to seek similar aid, potentially depleting her kingdom''s resources. However, she also understood that a true leader must sometimes take risks to protect her people.

After a moment of contemplation, she made her decision. "You shall have what you need," she declared. "But I ask something in return. When your village prospers again, I want you to share your abundance with any neighboring communities facing similar hardships. In this way, compassion shall ripple outward, strengthening our entire realm."

The girl''s eyes filled with grateful tears. "Thank you, Your Majesty! We shall honor your wish and spread this kindness far and wide."

True to her word, the queen provided the village with ample supplies. Spring arrived, and the villagers worked diligently to plant their crops. The harvest that year exceeded all expectations. Remembering their promise, they shared their bounty with neighboring villages experiencing difficulties.

This cycle of generosity continued year after year. The queen''s wisdom in fostering a culture of mutual support transformed her kingdom into a place where no one suffered alone. Communities that once barely knew each other now collaborated regularly, sharing resources and knowledge.

The young peasant girl, inspired by the queen''s example, eventually became a respected leader in her own village. She taught the younger generation about the importance of compassion and community, ensuring that the queen''s legacy would endure for generations to come.

As the queen grew older, she looked back on her reign with satisfaction. She had not conquered foreign lands or amassed great wealth, but she had created something far more valuable: a society built on kindness, cooperation, and mutual respect.

On her final day, the queen gathered her closest advisors and shared her most precious wisdom. "A kingdom''s true strength," she said, "lies not in its armies or treasures, but in the bonds of compassion that connect its people. Remember this, and our realm shall prosper long after I am gone."

Her words proved prophetic. Long after the benevolent queen passed away, her kingdom continued to thrive. Travelers from distant lands marveled at the harmony and prosperity they witnessed, often asking what secret magic sustained such remarkable unity.

The answer was simple yet profound: the queen had planted seeds of kindness that grew into a forest of community and compassion. Her legacy lived on in every act of generosity, every moment of mutual support, and every decision made with the welfare of all in mind.

And so, the tale of the benevolent queen became a treasured story passed down through generations, reminding all who heard it that true greatness comes not from power or wealth, but from the courage to lead with compassion and the wisdom to foster unity among all people.'
WHERE title = 'The Queen''s Tale';

UPDATE books 
SET content = 'On the small asteroid B-612, far removed from the troubles of the adult world, lived a young prince with golden hair. His tiny planet was home to three volcanoes—two active, which he used for heating his breakfast, and one extinct. He also had to deal with troublesome baobab seedlings that threatened to split his planet apart if left unchecked.

But most precious to the little prince was his rose—a vain and complicated flower that appeared one day and immediately captured his heart. Though she demanded constant attention and protection, he loved her deeply. However, her pride and his inexperience led to misunderstandings, and eventually, the little prince decided to leave his planet and explore the universe.

His journey took him to several neighboring asteroids, each inhabited by a peculiar grown-up. On the first asteroid, he met a king who claimed to rule over everything, including the stars, though he lived alone. "I do not tolerate disobedience," the king proclaimed majestically, though there was no one to disobey him.

The second asteroid belonged to a conceited man who heard nothing but praise. "Ah! Here comes an admirer!" he exclaimed upon seeing the little prince. But the little prince found such vanity tiresome and soon departed.

Next came an asteroid with a tippler who drank to forget the shame of drinking—a circular logic that baffled the young traveler. Then he visited a businessman who spent all his time counting stars, believing that owning them made him rich. The little prince couldn''t understand why anyone would want to own things they couldn''t enjoy.

A lamplighter on a tiny planet that turned once per minute earned the little prince''s respect. This was the first adult he''d met who seemed concerned with something other than himself, faithfully lighting and extinguishing his lamp according to orders, even though they no longer made sense.

Finally, the little prince arrived on Earth, landing in the African desert. His first encounter was with a poisonous snake who spoke in riddles about returning people to where they came from. Walking further, he discovered a garden filled with thousands of roses, identical to his beloved flower. This discovery devastated him. "I thought I had a unique flower," he reflected sadly, "and all I have is an ordinary rose."

But then he met a fox in the desert. "Please, tame me," the fox requested. "What does tame mean?" asked the little prince. The fox explained that to tame meant to create ties, to make someone unique in all the world. "What is essential is invisible to the eye," the fox taught him. "It is only with the heart that one can see rightly."

Through this friendship, the little prince understood that his rose was special not because she was different from other roses, but because she was his rose. He had watered her, protected her from drafts, and listened to her complaints and boasts. Time and care had made her unique.

The fox also shared another secret: "You become responsible, forever, for what you have tamed." These words weighed heavily on the little prince. He realized he had abandoned his rose, his responsibility.

It was then that he met a pilot whose plane had crashed in the desert. The pilot was trying desperately to repair his engine, but the little prince engaged him in conversation. Over the following days, as the pilot worked, the little prince told his story. The pilot, reminded of his own childhood when he had drawn a boa constrictor digesting an elephant (which adults had mistaken for a hat), found a kindred spirit in this mysterious boy.

As water supplies dwindled, the little prince and pilot searched for a well. Walking through the desert at night, the little prince spoke of his home. "What makes the desert beautiful," said the little prince, "is that somewhere it hides a well."

They found water at dawn, and it tasted sweeter than any drink because they had earned it through their journey. The pilot noticed that the little prince seemed melancholy, staring at the stars and thinking of his planet.

Finally, the little prince revealed his plan. To return home, he would allow the snake to bite him. His body was too heavy to carry back to his asteroid. The pilot, understanding but heartbroken, tried to convince him to stay, but the little prince''s responsibility to his rose called him home.

On the evening of the anniversary of his arrival on Earth, the snake fulfilled its promise. The little prince fell silently, like a tree falling, and his body disappeared. The pilot knew that the little prince had returned to his asteroid to care for his rose.

Years later, the pilot asks anyone who travels the desert to watch for a small boy with golden hair who laughs but refuses to answer questions. "If you should come upon this spot, please do not hurry on. Wait a little, just under the star. If a child comes to you, if he laughs, if he has golden hair, if he refuses to answer questions, you will know who he is. Please comfort me and write immediately that he has returned."

The story ends with the pilot reflecting on the little prince''s wisdom about what matters in life. The stars are beautiful because somewhere among them is a flower we cannot see. The desert is beautiful because somewhere it hides a well. And what makes them precious is invisible to the eye.'
WHERE title = 'The Little Prince';

UPDATE books 
SET content = 'Wilbur was a young pig born in the spring on the Arable family''s farm. As the runt of the litter, he was initially destined to be killed, but eight-year-old Fern Arable begged her father to spare him. "Please don''t kill it!" she cried. "It''s unfair!" Her father relented, and Fern raised Wilbur with loving care, feeding him from a bottle and taking him for walks in a baby carriage.

However, Wilbur soon grew too large to keep as a house pet. When he was about five weeks old, he was sold to Fern''s uncle, Homer Zuckerman, who owned a farm down the road. Wilbur was placed in a barn with various other animals, including sheep, geese, and a horse. At first, he felt lonely and frightened in his new environment.

One day, a voice came from above. "Do you want a friend, Wilbur? I''ll be your friend. I''ve been watching you all day, and I like you." Wilbur looked up to see a large grey spider hanging from the rafters. Her name was Charlotte A. Cavatica, though everyone simply called her Charlotte.

Charlotte and Wilbur quickly became the best of friends. Charlotte would tell Wilbur stories and answer his endless questions about life in the barn. She explained her work as a spider, catching flies and other insects in her web. Though some found her method of living gruesome, Wilbur came to understand that Charlotte was simply following her nature.

As summer progressed, Wilbur enjoyed his life on the farm. He loved his meals of slops mixed with skim milk, his mud baths, and his conversations with Charlotte. But one day, an old sheep delivered some terrible news: "They''re fattening you up because they''re going to kill you when the weather gets cold."

Wilbur was terrified. "I don''t want to die! I want to stay alive, right here in my comfortable manure pile with all my friends!" Charlotte promised to help him, though she wasn''t sure exactly how. "You shall not die," she declared. "I''m going to save you."

Charlotte thought carefully about her plan. She realized that humans were easily fooled by appearances and signs. That very night, she spun words into her web. The next morning, when Lurvy the hired hand came to feed Wilbur, he nearly fainted. In Charlotte''s web, glistening with morning dew, were the words "SOME PIG."

News of the miraculous web spread throughout the county. People came from miles around to see the pig with words written about him. Mr. Zuckerman was convinced that Wilbur was no ordinary pig and began treating him with special care. The plan was working—Wilbur was becoming too famous and valuable to kill.

Over the following weeks, Charlotte spun more messages: "TERRIFIC," "RADIANT," and finally "HUMBLE." Each word caused a sensation and reinforced the idea that Wilbur was extraordinary. The barnyard animals all contributed suggestions, though Charlotte made the final decisions about what to write.

As autumn approached, Mr. Zuckerman decided to take Wilbur to the county fair, where he would compete for a prize. Charlotte, despite being tired from laying her egg sac, agreed to accompany Wilbur. "You have been my friend," she told him. "That in itself is a tremendous thing."

At the fair, Wilbur faced stiff competition from a much larger pig named Uncle. Charlotte knew she needed to spin one final message to secure Wilbur''s safety. Weak and exhausted, she managed to create her masterpiece: the word "HUMBLE" in her web.

The plan succeeded. Wilbur won a special prize, and Mr. Zuckerman was so proud that he vowed never to think of killing such a famous pig. Charlotte had saved Wilbur''s life.

However, triumph came with heartache. Charlotte, having expended all her energy laying her eggs and spinning her last message, knew she was dying. "I was just trying to keep my promise to you," she told Wilbur weakly. "You have been my friend. That in itself is a tremendous thing."

Wilbur was devastated. "You can''t die, Charlotte! I''ll take care of you!" But Charlotte explained that this was simply the natural cycle of life. What mattered was that she had lived fully and loved deeply.

Before she died, Charlotte asked Wilbur to take her egg sac back to the barn and protect it. Though heartbroken, Wilbur agreed. With the help of Templeton the rat, he managed to bring the precious egg sac home.

Winter came, and Wilbur faithfully guarded Charlotte''s eggs. When spring arrived, the eggs hatched, releasing hundreds of tiny spiders. Most of them ballooned away on silken threads to start their own lives, but three stayed behind: Joy, Aranea, and Nellie. They became Wilbur''s new friends, though none could ever take Charlotte''s place.

As the years passed, generations of Charlotte''s descendants lived in the barn, and Wilbur was never lonely. He often thought about Charlotte and the words she had taught him about friendship and sacrifice. "It is not often that someone comes along who is a true friend and a good writer," he would reflect. "Charlotte was both."

Fern grew up and lost interest in spending every day in the barn, but she never forgot the magical summer when she had saved a pig and witnessed the extraordinary friendship between a spider and her pig. The barn remained a place where miracles could happen, where an ordinary pig could become extraordinary, and where true friendship could conquer even death.

Wilbur lived a long, comfortable life, always remembering the friend who had saved him with nothing more than her web, her words, and her unwavering love. And in the quiet moments of each day, he would look up at the doorway where Charlotte''s descendants spun their webs and smile, knowing that some friendships, like Charlotte''s words, last forever.'
WHERE title = 'Charlotte''s Web';